  "texts": [
    "In our review, as of July 2022, we found 93 published papers that reported evidence for the potential of audio-based COVID-19 classification.",
    "Of these 93 papers, 75 report an area under the curve (AUC) (or F1) of over 0.75, whereas 44 report a performance of above 0.90.",
    "Extended Data Table 1 summarizes nine highly cited datasets and their corresponding classification performance.",
    "Despite these encouraging results, concerns remain that the prediction models may not be transferable to real-world settings 11, 15, [18] [19] [20] [21].",
    "In some cases, data quality may be lowered by, for example, sampling biases, lack of verification of participants' COVID-19 status, a long delay between infection and audio recording, or small numbers of individuals who are SARS-CoV-2 reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-positive (COVID +) 21."
  ],
